description "For those of you unfamiliar with Cockney Rhyming Slang it involves finding a two or three word rhyme for the original word and then dropping the last word (or words) of the rhyme. In this case the original word is "stairs". The rhyme is "apples and pears". Then we drop the last bit of the rhyme and are left with "apples". So, instead of saying "going up the stairs", you would say "going up the apples". Makes you part of an exclusive club where outsiders just don't understand. Those of you of an American persuasion would not use the technique often, but there is one you would know. "I haven't got much bread" means "I haven't got much money". The rhyme derives from "bread and honey" = "money" I've got some more rhyming slang puzzles coming - hope you enjoy them."
